defaultThe market price of food reflects commercial supply and demand factors.  However, it is the intention of the retail sector to ensure that the cost of food products to the consumer is kept 
defaultas 
defaultlow
default as possible
default. This necessarily will have an impact on the ability of producers to match the demands from supermarkets.  
default&#xa0;
default2.2 
defaultProducers wish to see higher food prices in order to maintain viable margins. For 
defaultfarmers, where input prices have often risen at a rate above
default inflation, static pricing or even reduced returns
default,
default 
defaultmakes it harder for farmers to compete.
default&#xa0;
default2.3 
defaultIn this sense
default,
default the issue to resolve is essentially that between the producer and the retailer. 
defaultT
defaulthis should not exempt the impact of other parties in the food s
defaultupply chain, such as processors or packagers. 
default&#xa0;
default2.4 
defaultThe CLA believes it is incumbent
default on the retail sector to ensure
default the relationship between the producer and the retailer is both fair and equitable. To make farming more sustainable, there needs to be an eq
defaultuitable share of risk and profit along the food supply chain, and some form of investment from the larger retailers in the producer’s business
default,
default to help secure the ability to supply. Whilst it is accepted that a cheap food policy is being pursued by the Gov
defaulternment, there has to be a realisation that the increasing costs of producing food will lead to many exiting the industry
default,
default which is a threat to food security.
default&#xa0;
