default3.5 
defaultWhile a healthy domestic agriculture is an essential component of a secure food system in
default the UK, a balance is needed.  Total self-sufficiency would make the UK’s food supplies less secure rather than more secure.  If the UK refocused solely on domestic production and ignored external trade, there could be an unforeseen catastrophic event, suc
defaulth as a major crop failure or disease epidemic in livestock, which would leave the UK needing to rapidly source food from global markets. Diversity of supply is the key to resilience.
default&#xa0;
default3.6 
defaultTrading relationships themselves ar
defaulte
default a source of risk.
default In 2006, 26 c
defaultountries, including the UK, accounted for 90% of the UK’s food supplies, up from 22 countries in 1996.  In 2009, 34 countries each supplied the UK with at least 0.5% of its food imports. The Netherlands accounted for the highest share with 13%. According t
defaulto Defra
default,
default the vast majority of our food (69% in value) comes from trading partners in the EU. But, 
defaultthere is no guarantee that even our EU trading relationships will always remain stable. In
default 
defaultthe event of severe shortages of basic food stuffs, it is questiona
defaultble whether intra-EU trade would continue to operate smoothly.  While this may seem unlikely, there might be a need to consider contingency plans for dealing with the breakdown of the single market.  If EU countries did attempt to take protectionist action
default in a time of severe food shortages, the Commission would seek to ensure that the rules of the single market were upheld. But it may not be able to apply sanctions with sufficient speed.
