default4.1 
defaultIt is very difficult to make an accurate forecast of what value GM technology could bring to the UK food sector. This is because the current regulatory framework is so restrictive that the possibility for companies to develop GM products is very limited. A
defaults a result, UK food producers do not 
defaultcurrently 
defaultengage with the potential of such technologies
default,
default as it 
defaultis not commercially viable.
default&#xa0;
default4.2 
defaultGM techniques, used as part of a wider approach to food se
defaultcurity, can make a significant
default positive impact to food productio
defaultn in the UK. This is not just in how we can produce
default more from existing resources; 
defaultit also concerns how we can protect biodiversity, improve natural resource provision, and make contributions to animal welfare. It is therefore vital that food security, howe
defaultver it is defined, takes into account the indirect challenges that come with needing to produce more. 
defaultIn our view,
default the livestock and woodland sectors have arguably more to gain from such GM technologies, and subsequently more to contribute in food security
default policy.
default&#xa0;
default4.3 
defaultT
defaulthe net global economic benefits at farm level added by cultivating GM crops
default,
default rather than conventional varieties of crops
default,
default have been estimated at $14billion in 2010, and by 2011, almost 17 million farmers around the world planted GM crops, up from 15 million in 2010
default.
